 for bestpractices and # User Management

## Overview
Create a robust, enterprise-ready User Management module for LifeOps that provides an Admin interface to manage user accounts, roles, sessions, and audit logs. This module also integrates with Admin & Compliance Tools for org management, audit exports, usage controls, roles, and data retention policies, and contributes to the Admin Dashboard with enterprise settings, integrations, and compliance reporting. All UI must be designed for a dark, high-contrast, developer- and power-user oriented experience, with dense data presentation, precise controls, and traceable actions. Emphasize security, auditability, and reversible actions, with a strong emphasis on runtime safety and data integrity.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The User Management page is the Admin-facing control center for user accounts, roles, sessions, and audit logs, with built-in tooling to assign granular roles, revoke sessions, export audit trails, and view/approve actions in an auditable, auditable-first workflow.

Goals:
- Enable admins to create, modify, deactivate, or delete user accounts.
- Provide granular role assignment with scopes and permissions aligned to enterprise policy.
- Allow administrators to monitor and revoke user sessions in real time.
- Provide access to user-level audit logs and an export mechanism for compliance.
- Integrate with Org management, data retention policies, and audit/export tooling from Admin & Compliance Tools.
- Surface relevant compliance insights in the Admin Dashboard with enterprise reports and integrations status.

Features connected:
- Admin & Compliance Tools: Organization management, audit exports, usage controls, roles, data retention policies.
- Admin Dashboard: Centralized control plane for users, roles, enterprise settings, integrations, and compliance reports.

UI elements and how they should look:
- User Table: columns for Name, Email, Role, Status, Last Active, and Actions (View, Edit, Revoke Sessions, Delete).
- Role Assignment UI: inline or modal dialogs for assigning roles with scope pickers, per-resource permissions, and validation against org policies.
- Session Management: per-user session list with device, IP, last used, and Revoke All Sessions or individual session revoke actions.
- Audit Logs Access: a click-through to user action history, with filters (date range, action type, resource) and a cronjob/approval trace view if applicable.
- Admin tools surface: quick actions for enabling/disabling users, resetting passwords, role changes, and data retention policy toggles.
- Audit export: a dedicated action to export a user’s audit trail, with status, export URL, and download progress.
- UI guidance: dense data tables with sortable columns, consistent action button styling, clear confirmation dialogs for destructive actions, and consistent use of the left navigation and header chrome from the design system.

Visual guidance:
- Maintain the project’s dark UI aesthetic with high-contrast typography, minimal chrome, and tactile card surfaces for user details, audit artifacts, and session panels. Use accent red for critical alerts or irreversible actions, and teal/amber/purple sparingly for status indicators and data viz in the Admin Dashboard.

API integrations:
- No external APIs specified in this task. All data flows will be through the project’s internal APIs and the LifeOps orchestration layer where applicable, with auditability.

PROJECT CONTEXT:
- TARGET PAGE: User Management
- Description: Admin interface to manage user accounts, roles, sessions, and audit logs.
- Connected Pages/Tools: Admin Dashboard, Admin & Compliance Tools
- Data governance and security requirements per LifeOps: traceable agent-to-agent messages, schema-validated actions, full audit trails, reversible actions, and run artifacts.

## Components to Build
- UserManagementPage: main page container with tabs or sections for Users, Roles, Sessions, and Audit Logs.
- UserTable: grid displaying users with pagination, sorting, and batch actions.
- UserFormDrawer or Modal: create/edit user with fields for name, email, status, org membership, and password reset flow.
- RoleAssignmentPanel: multi-select/drag-select interface for role assignment with scope controls and policy validation.
- SessionListPanel: per-user session viewer with revoke actions and bulk revoke.
- AuditLogsPanel: per-user audit trail viewer with filters and export actions.
- AuditExportModal: handles export initiation, status tracking, and download URL.
- OrgManagementLink/Panel (integration touchpoint): quick navigation to org-level settings for a selected user.
- DataRetentionPolicySync: component interfacing with Admin & Compliance Tools to reflect org data retention settings.
- AdminDashboardWidgets: small dashboards/cards for compliance reports, integration statuses, and usage controls.

Technical details (data shapes and interactions):
- User entity: id, name, email, status (active/suspended/disabled), lastActive, roles (array of RoleRefs), orgId, createdAt, updatedAt.
- Role entity: id, name, permissions (array), scope (object with resourceType and resourceId or global), inheritedFromOrg (boolean).
- Session entity: id, userId, device, ip, lastUsed, valid (boolean), expiresAt.
- AuditLog entity: id, userId, action, resource, timestamp, actor, details (JSON), cronjobRunId (optional).
- Audit export task: id, userId, status (pending/in-progress/completed/failed), createdAt, completedAt, exportUrl.
- Org entity (for Org management integration): id, name, policies, retentionPolicy, usersCount.
- Data retention policy: retentionDays, policyName, scope (org-wide, user-level).
- API endpoints will be protected with RBAC; all responses should be validated and guard against null data.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Use React (with TypeScript) and a component library aligned with the design system.
- Ensure all array operations guard against null/undefined data:
  - Always use data ?? [] when mapping/filtering: (users ?? []).map(...)
  - Validate with Array.isArray(data) before map/filter: Array.isArray(roles) ? roles.map(...) : []
- Initialize React state for arrays: useState<User[]>([]) for user lists, useState<Role[]>([]) for roles, etc.
- Use proper nullish checks for API responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Provide responsive layout: desktop grid with a dense left navigation and a main content area; ensure accessibility via ARIA attributes, keyboard navigation, and focus management.
- UI patterns:
  - Data tables with sortable headers and pagination.
  - Modals/Drawers for create/edit forms with inline validation and inline error messaging.
  - Confirm dialogs for destructive actions (Delete, Revoke Sessions, Disable).
  - Toasts or toasts for success/error feedback.
  - Role picker with search and grouping; show current role assignments with quick remove.
- Data visualization in Admin Dashboard: minimal charts for user growth, active sessions, and audit activity using the project’s chart primitives; respect accessibility and color contrast requirements.
- Validation:
  - Email format validation; password strength checks during creation/reset; unique email enforcement at the UI level with server validation fallback.
  - Role/scope validation to ensure no privilege escalation beyond org policy.
- Security UI touches:
  - Password reset workflows should trigger a temporary token flow, not reveal passwords.
  - Sensitive actions require confirmation and optional MFA prompts if configured in the org.

### Backend
- API Endpoints (examples, outline; adapt to existing routing conventions):
  - GET /api/admin/users?orgId=...&page=...&size=...&search=...&sort=... -> User[]
  - POST /api/admin/users -> create user (payload: { name, email, orgId, roles })
  - PUT /api/admin/users/{id} -> update user (payload: { name?, email?, status?, roles? })
  - DELETE /api/admin/users/{id} -> delete user
  - POST /api/admin/users/{id}/sessions/revoke -> revoke all sessions or specific session
  - GET /api/admin/users/{id}/audit-logs -> AuditLog[]
  - POST /api/admin/users/{id}/audit-export -> initiate export -> { taskId, status }
  - GET /api/admin/audit-exports/{taskId} -> export status and URL
  - GET /api/admin/organizations/{orgId}/policy -> data retention and policy details
  - GET /api/admin/organizations/{orgId}/users-count -> counts
- Database tables (schema considerations):
  - users, roles, user_roles, sessions, audit_logs, audit_exports, organizations, data_retention_policies
- Functions to implement:
  - RBAC enforcement per route, with policy checks at the server.
  - Audit logging for admin actions (Create/Update/Delete, Role changes, Session revocations).
  - Data validation and normalization (e.g., ensure roles exist before assignment).
  - Anti-tamper and idempotent export initiation with idempotent handling for retries.
  - API input validation and sanitization.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - Frontend calls user endpoints, gets typed data, uses nullish defaults to guard against null data.
  - Role assignment and org policy checks occur server-side; UI provides immediate feedback with validation messages.
  - Audit logs are consumed by AuditLogsPanel; audit exports trigger background tasks with status tracked via AuditExport endpoints.
- Reconciliation with Admin & Compliance Tools:
  - Display org-level retention policies on the User page and reflect in UI around user data lifecycle.
  - When roles or org policies change, UI reflects policy changes with warnings and required re-authorization for privileged actions.
- State management:
  - Use a centralized data fetching layer (e.g., React Query or custom hooks) with stale-while-revalidate patterns.
  - Ensure arrays are initialized as empty and guarded in all selectors and render paths.

## User Experience Flow
- Admin lands on User Management from the Admin Dashboard.
- View the User Table: can search, sort by Last Active, filter by Status, paginate.
- Create a User: opens a drawer/modal with fields (Name, Email, Org, Roles). Validate inputs; submit; see success toast; user appears in table with assigned roles.
- Edit a User: open Drawer with current data; adjust name/email/status/roles; save; confirm changes reflect in the table; audit log records the change.
- Manage Sessions: click a user, open SessionListPanel; review active sessions; revoke individual sessions or all sessions for the user; receive success notification.
- View Audit Logs: open per-user audit trail; filter by action or date; export audit trail via Audit Export action; track export status.
- Role assignment: open RoleAssignmentPanel; assign roles with granular scopes; validate against org policies; save; see updated roles in the user row.
- Data retention and org policies: navigate to Org Management; view/update retention policies; UI reflects policy constraints on user data, and admin actions are gated accordingly.
- Admin Dashboard integration: view compliance reports, integration statuses, user growth, and usage controls charts. Hover/tooltip details show run artifacts and audit breadcrumbs.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models:
- User { id: string, name: string, email: string, status: 'active'|'suspended'|'disabled', lastActive: string | null, orgId: string | null, createdAt: string, updatedAt: string, roles: string[] }
- Role { id: string, name: string, permissions: string[], scope?: { resourceType: string, resourceId?: string }[], inheritedFromOrg?: boolean }
- Session { id: string, userId: string, device: string, ip: string, lastUsed: string, valid: boolean, expiresAt: string | null }
- AuditLog { id: string, userId: string, action: string, resource: string, timestamp: string, actor: string, details?: any }
- AuditExport { id: string, userId: string, status: 'pending'|'in-progress'|'completed'|'failed', createdAt: string, updatedAt: string, exportUrl?: string, reason?: string }
- Organization { id: string, name: string, policies: any, retentionPolicy: any }
- DataRetentionPolicy { orgId: string, policyName: string, retentionDays: number, scope: 'org'|'user' }

API Endpoints:
- GET /api/admin/users
- POST /api/admin/users
- PUT /api/admin/users/{id}
- DELETE /api/admin/users/{id}
- POST /api/admin/users/{id}/sessions/revoke
- GET /api/admin/users/{id}/audit-logs
- POST /api/admin/users/{id}/audit-export
- GET /api/admin/audit-exports/{taskId}
- GET /api/admin/organizations/{orgId}/policy
- GET /api/admin/organizations/{orgId}/users-count

Security:
- RBAC: require roles with appropriate permissions for each action (view, create, update, delete, manage sessions, export audits, manage org policies).
- Authentication: must be authenticated; enforce least privilege.
- Validation: server-side input validation; sanitize all inputs; guard against injection; audit trails for admin actions.

Validation:
- Frontend: form validations (email, required fields, role/policy validity), field-level error messages, and cross-field validations for policy compatibility.
- Backend: verify user existence, role validity, org policy compliance, and audit log integrity before persisting.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] All user data fetches guard against null data; UI renders with empty states when data is missing.
- [ ] Roles and scopes cannot be assigned beyond org policy; attempting to do so shows a clear error.
- [ ] All destructive actions (Delete User, Revoke Sessions) require explicit confirmation and are audit-logged.
- [ ] Session revocation and role updates reflect in real-time in the UI and are captured in audit logs.
- [ ] Audit export tasks can be initiated, show status, and provide a downloadable export URL upon completion.
- [ ] Data retention policies are visible and enforceable in the UI; policy changes propagate to related user data actions.
- [ ] All API responses are validated; client handles non-array data and missing fields gracefully without crashes.
- [ ] Accessibility checks pass (keyboard navigation, ARIA labels, readable contrast).

UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Dark, high-contrast UI with dense, data-rich presentation.
- Consistent left navigation with clear active states and expandable sections.
- Cards with subtle gradients, rounded corners, and soft shadows.
- Minimal but purposeful color accents to indicate alerts, statuses, and actions.
- Typography hierarchy as described; 8px baseline grid; generous panel padding for readability.
- Interactive elements with smooth 120–200ms transitions; focus rings and hover states.
- Ensure all components are responsive and accessible.

Visual Style

Color Palette
- Primary background: #0B0B0C
- Secondary surface: #151718
- Tertiary surface / panel outline: #1F1F20
- Primary text / headings: #FFFFFF
- Secondary text / meta: #9DA3A6
- Subtle text / disabled: #56595B
- Accent (action / alert): #FF3B30
- Neutral highlight / icon fill: #CFCFCF
- Soft highlight / gloss: #E6E7E8
- Chart/status accents: teal #00C2A8, amber #FFB020, purple #8B5CF6
- Borders / dividers: rgba(255,255,255,0.03)
- Gradients: #111213 → #1A1A1B

Typography & Layout
- Font: Inter (or SF Pro Display / Roboto fallback)
- Heading weights: 600–700, 20–28px
- Card titles: 14–16px, 500–600 weight
- Body: 12–14px, 400 weight
- Microcopy: 11–12px, 300–400 weight
- Spacing: 8px baseline grid; gutters 220–260px for sidebar; header 56–64px
- Alignment: left-aligned lists; dense vertical spacing in trees; grid layouts for card dashboards

Key Design Elements
- Card Design: dark elevated cards, 8–12px radius, gradient fill, subtle borders and shadows, hover lift
- Navigation: left vertical nav with expandable sections; active state indicator with accent pill
- Data Visualization: minimal charts with subdued gridlines; accent colors for series; tooltips with white text
- Interactive Elements: primary/secondary buttons; dark inputs; rounded toggles/chips; validation feedback
- Micro-interactions: 120–200ms transitions; clear affordances for actions

Design Philosophy
- Focused, dense, and legible dark UI optimized for admin workflows
- Emphasis on auditability, control, and policy-compliant actions
- Consistent visual language across User Management, Admin Dashboard, and Admin & Compliance Tools
- Provide quick scanning capabilities for user activity, audits, and policy enforcement
- Ensure reversibility, explainability, and traceability in all admin actions

Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety

CRITICAL: Follow these rules in ALL generated code to prevent runtime crashes.

1. Supabase query results: Always use nullish coalescing — data ?? [].
2. Array methods: Guard all calls.
   - (items ?? []).map(...)
   - Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
3. React useState for arrays/objects: Initialize with proper type, e.g., useState<User[]>([])
4. API response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
5. Optional chaining: Use obj?.property?.nested
6. Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

Connected Pages:
- Admin Dashboard: Administrative control panel with enterprise settings, integrations, and compliance reports.

Connected Features:
- Admin & Compliance Tools: Org management, audit exports, usage controls, roles, and data retention policies for enterprise compliance.

Generate the complete, detailed prompt now. for style.

CRITICAL DESIGN REQUIREMENTS:
- You MUST follow ALL design principles and patterns specified in the Design Reference above
- Do NOT deviate from the design specifications without explicit user permission
- Implement ALL visual design elements (colors, typography, spacing, shadows, animations) as specified
- Follow the layout patterns and component designs exactly as documented
- Ensure all interactions and micro-animations match the reference specifications

CRITICAL TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS:
- React 18.3.1, React Router 6.30.1
- Tailwind CSS v3 with tailwind.config.js and custom keyframes
- @tailwindcss/typography plugin for rich text content
- Tailwind CSS animations (NOT Motion library or framer-motion)
- Sonner for toasts
- Recharts for data visualization
- Native fetch() with API utilities in src/lib/api.ts
- Design system with CSS custom properties
- Use RGB color values for theming
- When Supabase is configured: use Edge Functions for LLM and server-only logic; never expose API keys in the client

=== TASK ===
# User Management

## Overview
Create a robust, enterprise-ready User Management module for LifeOps that provides an Admin interface to manage user accounts, roles, sessions, and audit logs. This module also integrates with Admin & Compliance Tools for org management, audit exports, usage controls, roles, and data retention policies, and contributes to the Admin Dashboard with enterprise settings, integrations, and compliance reporting. All UI must be designed for a dark, high-contrast, developer- and power-user oriented experience, with dense data presentation, precise controls, and traceable actions. Emphasize security, auditability, and reversible actions, with a strong emphasis on runtime safety and data integrity.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The User Management page is the Admin-facing control center for user accounts, roles, sessions, and audit logs, with built-in tooling to assign granular roles, revoke sessions, export audit trails, and view/approve actions in an auditable, auditable-first workflow.

Goals:
- Enable admins to create, modify, deactivate, or delete user accounts.
- Provide granular role assignment with scopes and permissions aligned to enterprise policy.
- Allow administrators to monitor and revoke user sessions in real time.
- Provide access to user-level audit logs and an export mechanism for compliance.
- Integrate with Org management, data retention policies, and audit/export tooling from Admin & Compliance Tools.
- Surface relevant compliance insights in the Admin Dashboard with enterprise reports and integrations status.

Features connected:
- Admin & Compliance Tools: Organization management, audit exports, usage controls, roles, data retention policies.
- Admin Dashboard: Centralized control plane for users, roles, enterprise settings, integrations, and compliance reports.

UI elements and how they should look:
- User Table: columns for Name, Email, Role, Status, Last Active, and Actions (View, Edit, Revoke Sessions, Delete).
- Role Assignment UI: inline or modal dialogs for assigning roles with scope pickers, per-resource permissions, and validation against org policies.
- Session Management: per-user session list with device, IP, last used, and Revoke All Sessions or individual session revoke actions.
- Audit Logs Access: a click-through to user action history, with filters (date range, action type, resource) and a cronjob/approval trace view if applicable.
- Admin tools surface: quick actions for enabling/disabling users, resetting passwords, role changes, and data retention policy toggles.
- Audit export: a dedicated action to export a user’s audit trail, with status, export URL, and download progress.
- UI guidance: dense data tables with sortable columns, consistent action button styling, clear confirmation dialogs for destructive actions, and consistent use of the left navigation and header chrome from the design system.

Visual guidance:
- Maintain the project’s dark UI aesthetic with high-contrast typography, minimal chrome, and tactile card surfaces for user details, audit artifacts, and session panels. Use accent red for critical alerts or irreversible actions, and teal/amber/purple sparingly for status indicators and data viz in the Admin Dashboard.

API integrations:
- No external APIs specified in this task. All data flows will be through the project’s internal APIs and the LifeOps orchestration layer where applicable, with auditability.

PROJECT CONTEXT:
- TARGET PAGE: User Management
- Description: Admin interface to manage user accounts, roles, sessions, and audit logs.
- Connected Pages/Tools: Admin Dashboard, Admin & Compliance Tools
- Data governance and security requirements per LifeOps: traceable agent-to-agent messages, schema-validated actions, full audit trails, reversible actions, and run artifacts.

